Introduction
************

The @{b}IconTools@{ub} are a collection of commands for creating and
manipulating Workbench icon images.  Before I started calling this
project @{b}IconTools@{ub} there had been several @{b}OptIcon@{ub} archives with other
tools like @{b}Icon2c@{ub} or @{b}IconMaker@{ub} included into it.  The reason for the
the tools included here being so widely spread is last but not least
due to the success of Martin Huttenloher's great MagicWB icon
collection.


@EndNode

@Node "OptIcon" "icontools.guide/OptIcon"
@Next "Icon2c"
@Prev "Introduction"
@Toc "Main"

OptIcon
*******

Abstract
========

Even if some users claim @{b}OptIcon@{ub} being the tool of their choice for
changing the number of bitplanes in their MagicWB icons, the main idea
behind @{b}OptIcon@{ub} is and was to optimize icons for size and speed.
@{b}OptIcon@{ub} reads @{b}.info@{ub} files and scans the icon image in order to
optimize the @{b}PlanePick@{ub} and @{b}PlaneOnOff@{ub} fields in the icon's @{b}Image@{ub}
structure.  This is a space-saving mechanism for image data.

     struct Image {
     
         /* ... */
     
         UBYTE PlanePick, PlaneOnOff;
     
         /* ... */
     };

Rather than defining the image data for every plane of the @{b}RastPort@{ub},
you need define data only for the planes that are not entirely zero or
one.  As you define your imagery, you will often find that most of the
planes @{i}are@{ui} just as color selectors.  For instance, if you're designing
a two-color icon to use colors one and three, and the icon will reside
in a five-plane display, bit plane zero of your imagery would be all
ones, bit plane one would have data that describes the imagery, and bit
planes two through four would be all zeroes.  Using these flags avoids
wasting all that memory in this way:  first, you specify which planes
you want your data to appear in using the @{b}PlanePick@{ub} variable.  For each
bit set in the variable, the next `plane' of your image data is blitted
to the display.  For each bit clear in this variable, the corresponding
bit in @{b}PlaneOnOff@{ub} is examined.  If that bit is clear, a `plane' of
zeroes will be used.  If the bit is set, ones will go out instead.
Note that if you want an @{b}Image@{ub} that is only a filled rectangle, you can
get this by setting @{b}PlanePick@{ub} to zero (pick no planes of data) and set
@{b}PlaneOnOff@{ub} to describe the pen color of the rectangle.

Installing OptIcon
==================

The @{b}OptIcon@{ub} executable comes in two versions: @{b}OptIcon.000@{ub} for all
Amigas and @{b}OptIcon.030@{ub} for Amigas with a MC-68030 processor.  You
simply have to copy one of those into your path (e.g. to @{b}C:@{ub}) and rename
it to @{b}OptIcon@{ub}:
     Copy CLONE FROM OptIcon.030 TO C:OptIcon

If you want to make use of the recursive-descent ablility of the
@{b}OptIcon.rexx@{ub} script then you should copy this into your @{b}rexx:@{ub} drawer
and make sure the script-flag @{b}s@{ub} ist set:
     Copy CLONE FROM OptIcon.rexx TO rexx:
     Protect FILE rexx:OptIcon.rexx ADD s

Invoking OptIcon
================

@{b}OptIcon@{ub} uses @{b}ReadArgs()@{ub} to parse the command line arguments with the
following template:
     FROM=NAME/A/M,DEPTH=PLANES/N,NOEXPAND/S,CRITICAL/S,REMAPV37/S,VERBOSE/S,SMART/S,ALL/S

@{b}FROM=NAME/A/M@{ub} (required, multiple)
     The name of the icon image file.  A trailing @{b}.info@{ub} is optional but
     not required.  Several icon image files can be specified.  If the
     @{b}ALL@{ub} switch is given, then @{b}OptIcon@{ub} recursively enters all
     directories passed via @{b}FROM@{ub}, collecting all icons.

@{b}DEPTH=PLANES/N@{ub} (numeric)
     With this option you can specify the number of bitplanes to save.

@{b}NOEXPAND/S@{ub} (switch)
     If the @{b}NOEXPAND@{ub} keyword is @{i}not@{ui} present in the command line, then
     @{b}OptIcon@{ub} will always write as many bitplanes as specified with the
     @{b}DEPTH=PLANES/N@{ub} option, even if bitplanes have to be added.  With
     the @{b}NOEXPAND@{ub} switch given, @{b}OptIcon@{ub} will not add any new planes.

@{b}CRITICAL/S@{ub} (switch)
     Commodore's @{b}PutDiskObject()@{ub} currently [icon.library 40.1 (15.2.93)]
     re-expands icon images using the PlanePick/PlaneOnOff mechanism
     and in fact @{b}PutDiskObject()@{ub} has quite a lot of problems doing so!
     For this reason @{b}OptIcon@{ub} will perform the PlanePick/PlaneOnOff
     optimization only if the keyword @{b}CRITICAL@{ub} is given in the command
     line!

@{b}REMAPV37/S@{ub} (switch)
     If the @{b}REMAPV37@{ub} switch is given in the command line, @{b}OptIcon@{ub} will
     map the colors 4-7 to the last 4 in the palette using the following
     algorithm:

       1. A bitplane mask is generated from all planes > 2 via @{b}OR@{ub}.
           (This mask has ones at those positions where any of the
          bitplanes > 2       has a 1 and has zeros only at those
          positions where all bitplanes > 2       have zeros.)

       2. The result is inverted and

       3. stamped with plane 2 via @{b}AND@{ub}.

       4. The resulting mask is set via @{b}OR@{ub} in all planes > 2

     There is obviously no need to expand the image data if the
     following expression is true for the @{b}PlaneOnOff@{ub} value @{b}p10@{ub}:
          p10 &~ %111 != 0

     When expanding an icon @{i}without@{ui} the @{b}REMAPV37@{ub} keyword given in the
     command line, the last 4 colors of the input image @{b}i@{ub} are mapped to
     the last 4 colors of the output image @{b}o@{ub} as follows:

       1. A bitplane mask is generated by an @{b}OR@{ub} of all bitplanes but
          the last.        (This mask has zeros only at those positions
          where all bitplanes       but the last have zeros and has
          ones otherwise.)

       2. The resulting mask is stamped via @{b}AND@{ub} with the last bitplane

       3. The result is set in all new bitplanes

     If any plane of @{b}i@{ub} but the last is entirely 1 then we can simply
     copy the last plane of @{b}i@{ub} to all new planes in @{b}o@{ub}

@{b}VERBOSE/S@{ub} (switch)
     This switch tells @{b}OptIcon@{ub} to print out some information about each
     icon and what @{b}OptIcon@{ub} is about to do with it.

@{b}SMART/S@{ub} (switch)
     With this switch, @{b}OptIcon@{ub} will examine @{b}WBDRAWER@{ub} and @{b}WBGARBAGE@{ub}
     icons more closely and if there is not really a drawer (or a file)
     behind the icon then the icon type is changed into @{b}WBTOOL@{ub}.  This
     is a great help if you want to use some drag'n drop application to
     update icon images which would have problems otherwise (bug?
     feature? hmmm...).

     @{i}Caution:@{ui} It is dangerous to call @{b}opticon ALL SMART@{ub} on @{b}ENV:@{ub} or
     @{b}ENVARC:@{ub} because this would change the type of the default icons
     @{b}sys/def_drawer.info@{ub} and @{b}sys/def_trashcan.info@{ub} (and perhaps some
     more) making them unusable for their initial purpose!

@{b}ALL/S@{ub} (switch)
     If this switch is given, @{b}OptIcon@{ub} recursively enters all
     subdirectories given via @{b}FROM@{ub}, collecting icons.

@{i}Example:@{ui} In order to remove all but the first 3 planes of the icon
image for the disk in drive @{b}DF0:@{ub} without adding any bitplanes you can
invoke @{b}OptIcon@{ub} as follows:
     OptIcon DF0:Disk PLANES=3 NOEXPAND

Notes
=====

Since the @{b}IconEdit@{ub} from Commodore will always save 8 bitplane icons the
above example might be of great use to you.  (Note that 3 plane images
are not only smaller but also faster!) Coming with @{b}OptIcon@{ub} is the
script @{b}PatchIcons@{ub} which will recursively descend all subdirectories of
a given path deleting all but the first 3 planes of all icon images in
that path.

@{b}OptIcon@{ub} now also allows you to expand your 8 or more color icons for
the use on a 16 or more color Workbench.  This is important due to the
new color system under OS3.x which always shifts the second four colors
to the end of the system palette.  Therefore you might want to adapt an
icon's color depth to the actual screenmode it is used on.

@{i}Note also:@{ui} @{b}OptIcon@{ub} will always overwrite your icon and does not support
a recursive descent.  This is why we wrote the @{b}ARexx@{ub} script
@{b}OptIcon.rexx@{ub} which offers all this to you.  Some people might never
even want to use @{b}OptIcon@{ub} directly but will always use @{b}OptIcon.rexx@{ub}.

@{i}Example:@{ui} I only have 8 colors on my Workbench and I often find icon
collections which come up with full 8 bitplane icons and image drawers
with no real drawer behind them.  Now on the one hand I don't want to
waste space and time for 5 bitplanes which I don't really need and on
the other hand I want to be able to use MH's drag'n drop tool
@{b}IconUpdate@{ub} to change my drawer images without having to care about
whether these are @{i}really@{ui} drawers or not.

Okay, I've downloaded @{b}pix/mwb/TobiIcons-2.0.lha@{ub} from the Aminet and
extracted it into my @{b}ram:@{ub} disk.  A drawer @{b}ram:Tobi-Icons/@{ub} had been
created there.  What I do now is I invoke my @{b}OptIcon.rexx@{ub} script and
change all the icons there into 3 plane icons and I change all the
faked @{b}DRAWER@{ub} icons into @{b}TOOL@{ub} icons:
     rx rexx:OptIcon.rexx FROM ram:Tobi-Icons ALL SMART PLANES 3

The magic happening there can also be achived without the @{b}.rexx@{ub} script
like that:
     List >ram:doit ALL FILES DIR ram:Tobi-Icons PAT #?.info +
       LFORMAT "OptIcon *"%p%n*" PLANES=3 NOEXPAND SMART"
     Execute ram:doit

OptIcon and MagicWB
===================

In these days, @{b}OptIcon@{ub} has become more and more used by people who use
Martin Huttenloher's MagicWB icon collection i.e. on Workbench screens
with more than only two bitplanes.  Due to the problems resulting from
the new coloring scheme (first-4/last-4 colors) as introduced with
OS3.x these icons look wrong if the number of bitplanes in the icon is
less than the number of bitplanes on the Workbench screen.  Of course
one could avoid this problem by giving each icon all eight bitplanes
(this is what Commodore's @{b}IconEdit@{ub} does) but this is a waste of space
and time since larger icons do not only eat up more disk space but are
also @{i}much@{ui} slower!

An easy way for solving this problem is @{b}OptIcon@{ub} on a ToolManager Dock or
AppIcon.  (Thanks to Mark Rose, who contributed his nice `Plane' icon
for the @{b}OptIcon@{ub} distribution.)

@{i}Example:@{ui} Suppose you have a 16 color Workbench and you find an 8 color
icon which looks wrong then you can simply call @{b}OptIcon PLANES=4@{ub} from
within ToolManager by simply dropping the icon on the dock.


@EndNode

@Node "Icon2c" "icontools.guide/Icon2c"
@Next "IconMaker"
@Prev "OptIcon"
@Toc "Main"

Icon2c
******

Abstract
========

Tools which manipulate existing icon images are widely spread but
actually when it comes to the point there most often is exactly one
switch missing: the one you need @{b};-)@{ub}.  @{b}Icon2c@{ub} reads a given @{b}.info@{ub} file
and writes out well documented and directly compilable C code.  This
code if compiled with a symbol @{b}TEST@{ub} defined (usual compiler option:
@{b}-DTEST@{ub}) will generate an executable which writes back the icon image
file to disk.  This allows you to modify any icon to your own needs -
with a text editor and a C compiler of your choice.

Installing Icon2c
=================

The @{b}Icon2c@{ub} executable comes in two versions: @{b}Icon2c.000@{ub} for all Amigas
and @{b}Icon2c.030@{ub} for Amigas with a MC-68030 processor.  You simply have
to copy one of those into your path (e.g. to @{b}C:@{ub}) and rename it to
@{b}Icon2c@{ub}:
     Copy CLONE FROM Icon2c.030 TO C:Icon2c

Invoking Icon2c
===============

@{b}Icon2c@{ub} uses @{b}ReadArgs()@{ub} to parse the command line arguments with the
following template:
     NAME/A,QUIET/S,TO/K

@{b}NAME/A@{ub} (required)
     Name of the icon image file.  A trailing @{b}.info@{ub} is optional but not
     required.

@{b}QUIET/S@{ub} (switch)
     If this switch is given then @{b}Icon2c@{ub} will not print any warnings.
     (More information about @{b}Icon2c@{ub}'s warnings can be found in the
     @{b}DrawerData@{ub} discussion further down.) Note: Warnings are allways
     directed to @{b}stderr@{ub} so that they always appear on the console (and
     not in the source code) even if the output is redirected from
     @{b}stdout@{ub} via @{b}>@{ub} or @{b}|@{ub}.

@{b}TO/K@{ub} (keyword required)
     This option allows you to specify the name of the generated C code
     file.  If not specified the standard output stream will be used
     which allows piping in a shell. E.g.:
          icon2c ram:disk.info | more

@{i}Example:@{ui} Suppose you want to generate C code from the disk icon of the
disk in @{b}DF0:@{ub}:
     Icon2c DF0:Disk QUIET TO RAM:diskicon.c

The Code Generated by Icon2c
============================

The code generated by @{b}Icon2c@{ub} always begins with some @{b}#include@{ub}s, which
define the structures and constants needed.

     #include <intuition/intuition.h>
     #include <workbench/workbench.h>
     #include <workbench/icon.h>

We will now discuss the generated output using a @{b}WBDISK@{ub} icon with two
images: one for the `normal' state and one for the `selected' state of
the icon.  The icon type @{b}WBDISK@{ub} is quite suitable for this tutorial
purpose because it needs all the structures an icon can have.  I've
created the code in the following examples by invoking @{b}Icon2c@{ub} like that:
     icon2c ram:disk.info >ram:diskinfo.c

The Image Data
--------------

For the `normal' icon image image (the one which we see if the icon is
not selected), an array @{b}gr_data@{ub} is generated.  Each line in the code
represents one line of pixels in the image.  As usual in the image
data, bitplanes are stored in ascending order:

     UWORD gr_data[] = {
     
       /* plane 0 */
     
       0x0000, 0x0000, 0x0000, ...
       0x0000, 0x0000, 0x0000, ...
       ...
     
       /* plane 1 */
     
       ...
     };

This array @{b}gr_data@{ub} is pointed to by the @{b}Image@{ub} structure @{b}gr@{ub} which - as
we will see later - is pointed to by the @{b}do_Gadget.GadgetRender@{ub} field of
the @{b}DiskObject@{ub} structure.  (This is why we use @{b}gr@{ub} here.)

     struct Image gr = {
       0,0,         /* LeftEdge, TopEdge     */
       47,36,3,     /* Width, Height, Depth  */
       gr_data,     /* ImageData             */
       7,0,         /* PlanePick, PlaneOnOff */
       NULL,        /* NextImage             */
     };

If the given icon has an alternate image, an array @{b}sr_data@{ub} and it's
@{b}Image@{ub} structure @{b}sr@{ub} are generated analog to @{b}gr_data@{ub} and @{b}gr@{ub}.  The @{b}sr@{ub}
structure is pointed to by the @{b}do_Gadget.SelectRender@{ub} field of the
@{b}DiskObject@{ub} structure.

The ToolTypes Array
-------------------

The icon ToolTypes are stored into @{b}tt@{ub}, a @{b}(char *)NULL@{ub}-terminated array
of strings.  Since our @{b}WBDISK@{ub} icon does not really need ToolTypes, we
only have a dummy here:
     char *tt[] = {
       "»»»» Icon by Martin Huttenloher ««««",
       NULL
     };

If there are no ToolTypes at all in the given icon, both is possible:
The @{b}tt@{ub} array is created and containes only one @{b}NULL@{ub} entry or the
@{b}do_ToolTypes@{ub} field in the @{b}DiskObject@{ub} structure contains a @{b}NULL@{ub} pointer.

The @{b}DrawerData@{ub} structure
------------------------

Icons of type @{b}WBDISK@{ub}, @{b}WBDRAWER@{ub} and @{b}WBGARBAGE@{ub} have a @{b}DrawerData@{ub}
structure which holds the information about the window which opens when
double-clicking the icon.  Icons of a different type do not have such a
structure but a @{b}NULL@{ub} pointer in the @{b}DiskObject@{ub}'s @{b}do_DrawerData@{ub} field.

The @{b}dd_NewWindow.FirstGadget@{ub} field holds a non-@{b}NULL@{ub} pointer every now
and then.  @{b}Icon2c@{ub} will print a warning message in these cases and
initialize the @{b}dd.dd_NewWindow.FirstGadget@{ub} field to @{b}NULL@{ub} in the
generated code.  The @{b}Gadget@{ub} structure will be included into the
generated code like this:
     #ifdef UNDEFINED
       struct Gadget <unknown> = {
     
         /* ... some strange stuff in here ... */
     
       };
     #endif /* UNDEFINED */

There also happens to be a non-@{b}NULL@{ub} pointer in the @{b}dd_NewWindow.Title@{ub}
field every now and then.  In this case as well a warning message will
be printed and the field in the generated code will be initialized to
@{b}NULL@{ub}.  However, the original string value will be available in a
comment if it is printable.

Here is the @{b}DrawerData@{ub} structure of our @{b}WBDISK@{ub} icon:

     struct DrawerData dd = {
       151,                  /* dd_NewWindow.LeftEdge    */
       54,                   /* dd_NewWindow.TopEdge     */
       347,                  /* dd_NewWindow.Width       */
       150,                  /* dd_NewWindow.Height      */
       255,                  /* dd_NewWindow.DetailPen   */
       255,                  /* dd_NewWindow.BlockPen    */
       NULL,                 /* dd_NewWindow.IDCMPFlags  */
       WFLG_SIZEGADGET
       | WFLG_DRAGBAR
       | WFLG_DEPTHGADGET
       | WFLG_CLOSEGADGET
       | WFLG_SIZEBRIGHT
       | WFLG_SIZEBBOTTOM
       | WFLG_SIMPLE_REFRESH
       | WFLG_REPORTMOUSE
       | WFLG_ACTIVATE
       | WFLG_WBENCHWINDOW,  /* dd_NewWindow.Flags       */
       NULL,                 /* dd_NewWindow.FirstGadget */
       NULL,                 /* dd_NewWindow.CheckMark   */
       NULL,                 /* dd_NewWindow.Title       */
       NULL,                 /* dd_NewWindow.Screen      */
       NULL,                 /* dd_NewWindow.BitMap      */
       92,                   /* dd_NewWindow.MinWidth    */
       68,                   /* dd_NewWindow.MinHeight   */
       65535,                /* dd_NewWindow.MaxWidth    */
       92,                   /* dd_NewWindow.MaxHeight   */
       WBENCHSCREEN,         /* dd_NewWindow.Type        */
       0,                    /* dd_CurrentX              */
       0,                    /* dd_CurrentY              */
       3,                    /* dd_Flags                 */
       0,                    /* dd_ViewModes             */
     };

The values of the @{b}dd_Flags@{ub} and @{b}dd_ViewModes@{ub} fields are not documented
in the includes.  Playing around with these values however has revealed
some information.  The @{b}dd_Flags@{ub} field is usually set to one of the
following:

@{b}1@{ub}
     If only files with an icon should be visible in this window.

@{b}2@{ub} or @{b}3@{ub}
     If all files should be visible, using the @{b}def_#?.info@{ub} default
     icons from @{b}env:sys/@{ub}.

The @{b}dd_ViewModes@{ub} field represents the sorting criteria of the files and
drawers listed in the window:

@{b}1@{ub}
     Graphical, view by icon

@{b}2@{ub}
     Textual, lexicographically sorted by name

@{b}3@{ub}
     Textual, sorted by date

@{b}4@{ub}
     Textual, sorted by size

The @{b}DiskObject@{ub} structure
------------------------

The @{b}DiskObject@{ub} structure @{b}icon@{ub} is the holder of all the other data.

     struct DiskObject icon = {
       WB_DISKMAGIC,                     /* do_Magic                */
       WB_DISKVERSION,                   /* do_Version              */
       NULL,                             /* do_Gadget.NextGadget    */
       5,                                /* do_Gadget.LeftEdge      */
       7,                                /* do_Gadget.TopEdge       */
       47,                               /* do_Gadget.Width         */
       37,                               /* do_Gadget.Height        */
       GFLG_GADGHIMAGE|GFLG_GADGIMAGE,   /* do_Gadget.Flags         */
       GACT_RELVERIFY|GACT_IMMEDIATE,    /* do_Gadget.Activation    */
       GTYP_BOOLGADGET,                  /* do_Gadget.GadgetType    */
       (APTR)&gr,                        /* do_Gadget.GadgetRender  */
       (APTR)&sr,                        /* do_Gadget.SelectRender  */
       NULL,                             /* do_Gadget.GadgetText    */
       0,                                /* do_Gadget.MutualExclude */
       NULL,                             /* do_Gadget.SpecialInfo   */
       0,                                /* do_Gadget.GadgetID      */
       (APTR)WB_DISKREVISION,            /* do_Gadget.UserData      */
       WBDISK,                           /* do_Type                 */
       "SYS:System/DiskCopy",            /* do_DefaultTool          */
       &tt[0],                           /* do_ToolTypes            */
       NO_ICON_POSITION,                 /* do_CurrentX             */
       NO_ICON_POSITION,                 /* do_CurrentY             */
       &dd,                              /* do_DrawerData           */
       NULL,                             /* do_ToolWindow           */
       8192,                             /* do_StackSize            */
     };

The @{b}TEST@{ub} code
-------------

When compiling the generated code with a symbol @{b}TEST@{ub} defined, then an
executable will be generated which writes the icon to disk via
@{b}PutDiskObject()@{ub}.  Together with a C compiler and a text editor of your
choice we now have the most powerful tool for manipulating Workbench
icons you can think of. @{b}(-:@{ub}

@{i}Example:@{ui} Let's assume you called @{b}Icon2c@{ub} and saved your Ram Disk icon to
@{b}ram:foo.c@{ub}:
     Icon2c ram:disk.info >ram:foo.c
Now you compile the file @{b}foo.c@{ub} with Dice C:
     dcc -2.0 -DTEST ram:foo.c
and the resulting executable @{b}ram:foo@{ub} can be used to write the icon back
to @{b}ram:disk.info@{ub}
     ram:foo ram:disk

Here is the @{b}main()@{ub} procedure of @{b}foo.c@{ub}:

     #ifdef TEST
     #include <intuition/intuitionbase.h>
     #include <stdlib.h>
     #include <stdio.h>
     
     extern struct Library *OpenLibrary(STRPTR, ULONG);
     extern void CloseLibrary(struct Library *);
     extern LONG IoErr(void);
     extern BOOL PrintFault(LONG, STRPTR);
     extern BOOL PutDiskObject(char *, struct DiskObject *);
     
     struct IconBase *IconBase;
     
     int main(int argc, char **argv)
     {
       if(argc == 2)
       {
         if( (IconBase= (struct IconBase *)OpenLibrary(ICONNAME,36)) )
         {
           if( !PutDiskObject(argv[1],&icon) )
             PrintFault(IoErr(),argv[1]);
           CloseLibrary(IconBase);
         }
         else printf("%s: no %s.\n",*argv,ICONNAME);
       }
       else printf("usage: %s <filename>\n",*argv);
     
       return IoErr();
     }
     #endif /* TEST */


@EndNode

@Node "IconMaker" "icontools.guide/IconMaker"
@Next "Master Index"
@Prev "Icon2c"
@Toc "Main"

IconMaker
*********

Abstract
========

Suppose you painted some brushes and now you want to make icons from
them.  Or let's assume you've downloaded some brushes and you don't
know how they look like.  This is where it comes to @{b}IM@{ub} - the @{b}IconMaker@{ub}.
@{b}IM@{ub} creates icons from brushes and offers you the best possibility for a
preview: the Workbench with all its functions!  @{b}(-:@{ub}

Installing IconMaker
====================

Simply copy @{b}IM.000@{ub} (or @{b}IM.030@{ub} if you have a MC-68030 Amiga) somewhere
into your path (e.g. to @{b}C:@{ub}) and rename it to @{b}IM@{ub}.  For example:
     Copy im.030 TO c:im

Invoking IconMaker
==================

@{b}IconMaker@{ub} uses @{b}ReadArgs()@{ub} to parse the command line arguments with the
following template:
     FROM=NORMAL/K/A,SELECTED/K,
     IW=ICONWIDTH/K/N,IH=ICONHEIGHT/K/N,MINSIZE/S,
     TYPE/K,HIGHLIGHT/K,
     IX=ICONX/K/N,IY=ICONY/K/N,
     TOOLTYPES/K/M,STACKSIZE/K/N,DEFAULTTOOL/K,
     WX=WINDOWX/K/N,WY=WINDOWY/K/N,WW=WINDOWWIDTH/K/N,WH=WINDOWHEIGHT/K/N,
     TO/K/A

@{b}FROM=NORMAL/K/A@{ub} (required, keyword required)
     The specified IFF/ILBM brush will be used for the normal image of
     the icon.  This argument @{i}must@{ui} be present in the command line.

@{b}SELECTED/K@{ub} (keyword required)
     The specified IFF/ILBM brush will be used for the selected image
     of the icon.  If present in the command line, an implicit
     @{b}HIGHLIGHT=IMAGE@{ub} is used.

@{b}TO/K/A@{ub} (required, keyword required)
     The name of the icon @{i}without@{ui} the trailing @{b}.info@{ub} which is appended
     automatically by @{b}PutDiskObject()@{ub}.

@{b}IW=ICONWIDTH/K/N@{ub} (numeric, keyword required)
@{b}IH=ICONHEIGHT/K/N@{ub} (numeric, keyword required)
     The dimensions of the icon image.  Smaller values than those of the
     brush(es) will use the top/left corner of the image, larger values
     will fill up the icon image's bottom/right border with 0's

@{b}MINSIZE/S@{ub} (switch)
     If the two IFF/ILBM brushes differ in size then the resulting icon
     image normally has the dimensions of the larger brush.  However,
     if the @{b}MINSIZE@{ub} switch is present in the command line, the
     dimensions of the smaller brush are used.

@{b}TYPE/K@{ub} (keyword required)
     By default, @{b}IM@{ub} will use @{b}TYPE=PROJECT@{ub} and create a project icon
     with the default tool @{b}MultiView@{ub}.  The @{b}TYPE@{ub} parameter is parsed
     with the following template:
          DISK/S,DRAWER/S,TOOL/S,PROJECT/S,GARBAGE/S

@{b}HIGHLIGHT/K@{ub} (keyword required)
     This argument specifies the highlighting method of the icon, i.e.
     what happens when the icon is selected.  If a @{b}SELECTED@{ub} image is
     specified, then @{b}IM@{ub} implicitly assumes @{b}HIGHLIGHT=IMAGE@{ub}.  The
     @{b}HIGHLIGHT@{ub} parameter is parsed with the following template:
          COMPLEMENT/S,BACKFILL/S,IMAGE/S

@{b}IX=ICONX/K/N@{ub} (numeric, keyword required)
@{b}IY=ICONY/K/N@{ub} (numeric, keyword required)
     By default the created icon has no fix position.  These two
     options allow an exact positioning of the created icon.

@{b}TOOLTYPES/K/M@{ub} (keyword required, multiple)
     Any number of ToolTypes can be specified.  By default, @{b}IM@{ub} uses
          TOOLTYPES "FILETYPE=ILBM"

@{b}STACKSIZE/K/N@{ub} (numeric, keyword required)
     The default stack size for @{b}TYPE=TOOL@{ub} icons.

@{b}DEFAULTTOOL/K@{ub} (keyword required)
     The default tool for @{b}TYPE=PROJECT@{ub} and @{b}TYPE=DISK@{ub} icons.

@{b}WX=WINDOWX/K/N@{ub} (numeric, keyword required)
@{b}WY=WINDOWY/K/N@{ub} (numeric, keyword required)
@{b}WW=WINDOWWIDTH/K/N@{ub} (numeric, keyword required)
@{b}WH=WINDOWHEIGHT/K/N@{ub} (numeric, keyword required)
     The window parameters for @{b}TYPE=DRAWER@{ub}, @{b}TYPE=DISK@{ub} or @{b}TYPE=GARBAGE@{ub}
     icons.

@{i}Example:@{ui} Let's assume you have @{b}DOpus5@{ub} and you want to see all brushes
in the @{b}Images/@{ub} and @{b}Images2/@{ub} drawer.  You simply have to do the
following:

     List >RAM:doit ALL FILES DIR DOpus5:Images/ DOpus5:Images2/ +
       PAT ~(#?.info) LFORMAT "IM FROM *"%p%n*" TO *"%p%n*""
     
     Execute RAM:doit

By default, @{b}IM@{ub} creates a project icon with the default tool @{b}MultiView@{ub}
and ToolType @{b}FILETYPE=ILBM@{ub}.  This is what I need in most cases when
using @{b}IM@{ub} for the above purpose.

Bugs
====

@{b}IM@{ub} does not remap the colors in your brushes to Workbench colors.  This
may or may not be implemented in the future.  Please mail me if you
really need such a feature.


@EndNode

